inn1.comm: Joyce tried to pull but failed to get over the ball and skyed it to midwicket
pulled long hop straight to backward square-leg. What an inspired bowling change!
driven square, slightly in the air, but safely between the fielders
wide down the leg side, bounced awkwardly in front of the wicketkeeper who still should have stopped it. Five runs gifted.
driven at catching height past White at backward point, but it would have been a remarkable take had he held it.
drove a wide and overpitched ball to Trent Johnson at short extra cover
inside edge which sneaked past Trescothick's off stump
edged high and wide past first slip
lofted drive just short of the long-on boundary
at last ... Bell comes down the track and edges through the vacant slip area for four
TrescothickÂ’s 11th ODI hundred brought up with a straight drive to long on. He started well but became subdued as Bell got bogged down at the other end.
a good bouncer which Bell shapes to hook but wisely pulls out of the shot
well held at long on trying to up the tempo

the end of an uninspiring innings, Bell caught at midwicket to a rare aggressive shot. While he was trying to play his way back into Test reckoning, it was hardly the big hitting and improvisation this capacity crowd expected
the sixth catch, Dalrymple coming down the wicket but top-edging to fine leg where Mooney clung on, albeit with more than a hint of a juggle
slower ball which ended up as a full toss and which was rightly smashed through midwicket for four
straight drive over long on
the first six of the innings, a slower ball wonderfully driven over long on and superbly held by a steward
excellent catch  at third man as Chapple gave himself room and attempted to cut over the top
heaved from outside off stump through midwicket
attempting a slower ball, all he managed was a ballooning full toss

inn2.comm: oops, wide down the leg side
and this one was even wider, swinging down the leg and giving Jones no chance
Harmison finds his line, the ball lifts too much for Joyce's backward defensive stroke which is a bit late and takes an inside edge into the stumps
wide and cut behind square
started wide of off stump and got wider. Harmison's radar is a bit awry here
fast and short, striking Bray
lovely backfoot drive square
loud shout for lbw but pitching outside leg
that was quick - 91.4mph - and the ball was in the wicketkeeper's gloves by the time Botha played his stroke
lofted over mid-on off the back foot
superbly timed push straight back past the bowler
caught in the gully
short, appeal for a catch behind by Jones but Plunkett not remotely interested
pitched up, textbook drive square through the covers
uppish drive inches short of a tumbling Dalrymple at short extra cover
loose drive staright through where first slip would have been standing ... had he not been moved to a wide second slip!
risky run, Collingwood's throw just missed but had he hit, Botha was not even in the frame
driven straight and hard back down the ground
Harmison brought back into the attack and an immediate reward as McCallan tried to run the ball to third man, got the thinest of edges and Jones held an oh-so-simple catch
quick single, misfielded
the wheels are beginning to come off now as another wicket falls as Gillespie chipped a slower ball to extra cover
great shot first up, a cracking drive through the covers
IrelandÂ’s slim chances have now all but gone as Harmison strikes again, Johnston cutting a short ball straight to Collingwood at backward point
Harmison continues to spray the ball around
a carbon copy of the previous ball. He's given away too many extras and seems to be trying a little bit too hard
